  "text": "Light chain levels were determined by quantitative immunoblotting. Tissues and cells were homogenized in buffer D (10 mM Hepes, 150 mM NaCI, 1 mM EGTA, 0.5 mM MgC12, 0.02% NAN3, 0.05% PMSE pH 7.2), and then centrifuged at 1,000 g, 30 rain. The resulting supernatants were boiled for 10 rain, and then centrifuged at 10,000 g for I0 min, leaving the clathrin light chains in solution while the heavy chains precipitate along with most of the other cellular proteins . Preliminary studies were conducted to ensure that both light chains were equally boiling resistant. Boiled tissue homogenates were reduced and run on a pair of 10% polyacrylamide gels. Dilutions of either purified adrenal LCa or LCb were also run on each gel (starting at 100 ng) to generate a standard curve. Proteins were transferred to nitrocellulose (14 V, 90 rain) and blots incubated overnight with 1% nonfat milk in TBS (10 mM Tris; 150 mM NaC1), pH 7.4, followed by primary antibody (10/~g/ml in 1% milk in TBS) for 4 h at room temperature, mAbs XI6 (anti-LCa) and LCB.1 (anti-LCb) were used for LCa and LCb quantitation, respectively. Antibody binding was detected following a 2-h incubation with 1251-rabbit anti-mouse IgG (0.5 × 106 cpm/ml in TBS) and autoradiography [CITATION_1] . Standard curves were plotted as band density versus nanograms of light chain standard yielding linear plots. Only those standard curves of four points or more with an r 2 value >0.95 were used to calculate quantities in tissue and cell samples. In addition, only numbers that fell within the standard curve were acceptable since there was no guarantee of linearity upon extrapolation. The relative quantities of light chains obtained for unknown samples are reported in Table I as a ratio of LCa to LCb (ng LCa/ng LCb).",
